The meeting (led by Rakesh, explaining to what seems like Vanshika) covered a DQ check table with an SCD-style active flag pattern. The core problem: when a check passes on re-run, the previous "failed + active" record needs to be deactivated. Two approaches were proposed to handle this in Spark/Oracle.
The data model (from Image 2):
cob_date | dwh_business_date | row_type | instance | status | active_flag | N (inactive?)
The active_flag = Y marks records that still need tracking (open failures). When reprocessed and passed, the old Y record must flip to N (inactive) and get an effective_end_timestamp.

Approach 1 — Stage table + Oracle MERGE
The Spark job writes check results to a stage (STG) table first using df.write(append). Then a custom Scala Oracle utility (JDBC, autocommit=false) fires a native Oracle MERGE statement — not a Spark operation. The MERGE logic:

If the business key (recon_engine + data_type + instance + dwh_business_date) matches an existing active record in the Check (Chk) table → update active_flag = N and set effective_end_timestamp
If no match → insert the new record from STG into Chk as a fresh active entry

Stage table rerun safety: Before each run, a DELETE + INSERT pattern is used on the stage table (not a Spark overwrite) — again via JDBC — so only one version of each execution exists in STG.

Approach 2 — No stage table, scan open failures directly
Skip the stage table entirely. Each day's run scans the Check table itself for all still-open (active_flag = Y, status = Fail) records across all previous dates, combines them with the current day's fresh check results, and appends everything via df.write(append). No MERGE needed. But the old failed records are never deactivated — they just accumulate, and the process always re-picks them up as long as they stay Y.

