So the DELETE solves three things:
1. Idempotency — you can rerun the job any number of times and always get the same clean result in CHK. DELETE ensures STG has exactly one copy before each write.
2. No cross-run contamination — yesterday's STG rows don't bleed into today's MERGE. Each run operates on a clean, fresh STG slice.
3. Correctness of the MERGE — the MERGE assumes one STG row per business key. The DELETE is what guarantees that assumption holds. Without it, the MERGE's WHEN NOT MATCHED THEN INSERT fires multiple times for the same key, producing duplicate CHK rows.
This is exactly what Rakesh means when he says "your stage table should be like a once a copy of that given execution." The DELETE is what enforces that "once a copy" guarantee.You said: why approach 2 not upto markwhy approach 2 not upto mark15 JunClaude responded: Good question.Good question. Let me break it down clearly.
Approach 2 works on a simple idea — instead of a MERGE, just scan CHK every day for all open failures (active_flag = Y, status = Fail) across all previous dates, combine them with today's fresh results, and df.write(append) everything into CHK directly.
On the surface it sounds simpler. But it breaks down in several important ways:

Problem 1 — CHK keeps growing with no deactivation
Every day you append new rows. The old failed rows from yesterday are never touched — they stay in CHK forever with active_flag = Y. So for a break that has been failing for 10 days, CHK has 10 open active rows for the same business key. There is no single source of truth for "what is the current state of this check."
Your dashboard query WHERE active_flag = 'Y' AND status = 'Fail' returns 10 rows for the same key instead of 1. You cannot tell which one is the latest. The table becomes meaningless for reporting.

Problem 2 — No audit trail of when something changed
In Approach 1, when a check moves from Fail to Pass, the MERGE stamps effective_end_ts on the old record and inserts a fresh Pass row. You know exactly when the break was resolved.
In Approach 2, the old Fail rows just keep sitting there with active_flag = Y forever. Even after the check eventually passes, the old Fail rows are never closed. There is no timestamp telling you when it was resolved. Your audit history is completely lost.

Problem 3 — No way to distinguish current state from history
In Approach 1 the distinction is clean:
active_flagmeaningYcurrent version — this is the truth right nowNhistorical — superseded, closed with end_ts
In Approach 2 everything is active_flag = Y — both the stale rows from 5 days ago and today's fresh result. There is no way to filter to just the current state without knowing which row was inserted last, which means you'd need to do a MAX(insert_ts) or ROW_NUMBER() trick on every query. And even that becomes unreliable if insert timestamps are not precisely tracked.

Problem 4 — The scan gets heavier every day
Each day the job scans the entire CHK table to find all open failures across all previous dates. As days accumulate, that scan covers more and more rows — including rows that were already picked up and reprocessed many times before. There is no natural cutoff. By week 3 you are scanning 3 weeks of accumulated appended rows just to find which ones are still open.
In Approach 1, the MERGE only touches the rows in STG — a small, precise, single-execution snapshot. CHK is never full-scanned for this purpose.

Problem 5 — Rerun safety is broken
In Approach 1, if the job reruns, the DELETE on STG ensures CHK only ever gets one clean version per execution.
In Approach 2, if the job reruns, df.write(append) fires again on CHK directly. Now CHK has duplicate rows for today's run — two identical active rows for the same business key on the same date. There is no DELETE step protecting CHK, and since Spark cannot do a targeted delete on Oracle via df.write, you have no clean way to fix this. The table is now corrupted.

Summary — the core problem
Approach 2 treats CHK as a pure append log, not as a state table. That works fine if you only ever need to answer "did this check ever fail?" But your requirement is to answer "is this check currently failing?" — and that requires being able to deactivate old versions when new results come in. df.write(append) cannot do that. Only a MERGE can. And that is precisely why Approach 1 exists.
Rakesh hints at this directly when he says:

"Now, now, here we wanted to update the previous entries of the active flag, right? So what will happen is that if I keep everything as open... you have to scan only the previous day's data where the records are failed."

He is describing the workaround Approach 2 forces you into — and immediately flagging that it is a compromise, not a clean design.
